glish <i>Hereweald</i>), particularly in Suffolk, where there was also post-medieval confusion with   Hurrell  . These all go back to an ancient Germanic personal name composed of the elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>wald</i> ‘rule’, which is attested in Europe from an early date; the Roman historian Tacitus records a certain <i>Cariovalda</i>, chief of the ancient Germanic tribe of the Batavi, as early as the 1st century  AD  See also   Herald  .","English: habitational name from Harrold (Bedfordshire), from Old English <i>hār</i> ‘gray’ + <i>wald</i> ‘large tract of woodland, high woodland’.","Irish: this name is of direct Norse origin (see 1 above), but is also occasionally a variant of   Harrell   and   Hurrell  . Spellings without final <i>d</i> have been adopted as the Anglicized form of the Gaelic <i>Ó hEarghail</i> (see   Harrell  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Airoldi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Chantal, Germaine, Herve, Marcel, Rosaire.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the old personal name <i>Airoldo</i>, a variant of <i>Aroldo</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hariwald</i>, composed of the elements <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>wald</i> ‘power, authority’; see   Harold  . This surname is also found in France, but to French Canada it was nevertheless brought from Italy."]},{"name":"Haroldson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Helmer.","Americanized form of Norwegian <b>Haraldsen</b> and Swedish <b>Haraldsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Harald</i>, Old Norse <i>Haraldr</i> (see   Harold  ). Compare   Haraldson   and   Haroldsen  ."]},{"name":"Harreld","meanings":["English: variant of   Harold  ."]},{"name":"Harrod","meanings":["English: variant of   Harold  . Compare   Herod  ."]},{"name":"Hurrell","meanings":["English: nickname presumably for someone with shaggy or unkempt hair, from a diminutive of Old French <i>hure</i> ‘hair’.","Irish (Antrim): possibly an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEarghail</b> ‘descendant of <i>Earghal</i>’, a variant of <b>Fearghal</b> (see   Farrell  ,   Arrell  , and   Harrell  )."]},{"name":"Haraldson","meanings":["Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Haraldsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Harald</i>, Old Norse <i>Haraldr</i> (see   Harold  ). This is also an Americanized form of the Norwegian cognate <b>Haraldsen</b>. Compare   Haralson  ,   Haroldsen  ,   Haroldson  , and   Harrelson  ."]},{"name":"Harrold","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Harold  ."]},{"name":"Harral","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Harold  ."]},{"name":"Harrell","meanings":["English: variant of   Harold  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEarghail</b> ‘descendant of <i>Earghal</i>’, a variant of the personal name <i>Fearghal</i> (see   Farrell  )."]}]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Ann Harold was born in 1460, in England, United Kingdom. She married Robert de Arden in 1493. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1520, in her hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1460–1520":"1460–1520","1450–1517":"1450–1517","1506–1571":"1506–1571","1520":"1520","1571":"1571","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1506":"1506","1517":"1517",", 1493":"1493","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fi":{"1460–1520":"1460–1520","1450–1517":"1450–1517","1506–1571":"1506–1571","1520":"1520","1571":"1571","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1506":"1506","1517":"1517",", 1493":"1493","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fr":{"1460–1520":"1460–1520","1450–1517":"1450–1517","1506–1571":"1506–1571","1520":"1520","1571":"1571","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1506":"1506","1517":"1517","